    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_544486032" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/544486032" />
    <a title="Marnie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/229744-marnie"><img alt="Marnie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1195328507p2/229744.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/544486032?book_show_action=true">Feb 23, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marnie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marnie" href="/user/show/229744-marnie">Marnie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audiobook 9780062262479" href="/book/show/15983708-beyond-belief">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer544486032" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13370458357210237932">It really is wild to think how brainwashing happens. And it is so frustrating to watch the product of it. The people who are critical of this book and of Jenna saying things like she could have left far earlier had she wanted to probably don&apos;t understand the power of brainwashing. In Jenna&apos;s case, it was what she was born into and the only way of life she knew. So while it is easy for us on the outside to look in and be frustrated that she didn&apos;t do something sooner, it is also pretty unfair of </span>
  <span id="freeText13370458357210237932" style="display:none">It really is wild to think how brainwashing happens. And it is so frustrating to watch the product of it. The people who are critical of this book and of Jenna saying things like she could have left far earlier had she wanted to probably don't understand the power of brainwashing. In Jenna's case, it was what she was born into and the only way of life she knew. So while it is easy for us on the outside to look in and be frustrated that she didn't do something sooner, it is also pretty unfair of us to react in that way. <br /><br />This was a very interesting and shocking (and horrific and sad and criminal and and and) inside account of being raised in the upper echelon of Scientology Society. Having parents in the Sea Org (highest ranking members of Scientology), Jenna Miscavige gives us the details of being raised within the walls of this organization. Children are separated from their parents and partake in manual labor as part of their daily routine, seeing their parents for only a few hours a week if possible. Being the niece of David Miscavige, the head honcho, Jenna's life is a little better than others for the first few years of his tenure. But as her brother and then her parents bow out of the church, which is considered the worst of the worst, Jenna is made to suffer and pay the price with extra security checks (confessional-type questioning sessions that don't end until the auditor gets the answer he's looking for), manual labor, separation from her friends, not being able to marry her fiance, etc. She does finally get to marry him and things improve for a small time, but then revert back.<br /><br />When she has finally had enough, her husband won't leave the church with her, as he is too afraid he'll never be able to talk to his family again. So she decides to stay (and the church first tells her she can't and then says she can but they'll be separated, which her hubs doesn't go for this time around). After some serious manipulation by the church, he starts to get a clearer head and they leave together. After they leave, they are followed on the outside and can't seem to get away for a while. <br /><br />Jenna tells her story in what I felt was a very respectful, modest way. I admire the fact that it wasn't as scathing as I imagine I'd feel having been manipulated and robbed of not only a childhood, but of a normal upbringing (yes, we can argue about what "normal" is, i know).<br /><br />It is hard to believe that the things endured by these people are legal, all in the name of religion. </span>
  <a data-text-id="13370458357210237932" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


